snippet.textDisplay:
British media is over hyping this performance (because they have to). AJ is a money machine for Sky, Matchroom and DAZN. He is their dependable cash cow. But, after all the flack Wlad took over the years, for this EXACT type of performance against similarly out of shape opponents, why are universally now hyping the same thing to this degree? It was a solid boxing show. A safety-first performance that easily ensure a points victory.

But it WAS NOT a Fury-esque boxing "masterclass." And it is devoid of the warrior-like fearlessness of the seemingly always-in-search-of-the-KO Wilder.

AJ did what he had to do, because of his inmate vulnerabilities - his reckless abandon in the pocket and his suspect chin (and temples). But Ruiz' condition absolutely needs to be taken into account. The guy looked like he had been pulled off vacation. Why are we hyping this?

This kind of excitement and hype can come ONLY AFTER AJ steps up and takes on either Wilder or Fury - consistently the best performers of recent times.

AJ is most certainly a top 5 fighter. But there's good reason he hasn't faced anyone inside the top 3 (Wlad can count, but Fury already burst that bubble far earlier).

Saying "don't believe the hype" might be harsh on AJ. But I'll believe it when it's actually there.

AJ, Wilder and Fury are all in their prime. They all need to fight each other before it's just a little too late.
